Coronavirus guidance is being updated.
Read the Prime Minister’s address for the latest information.

Lebanon has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Lebanon, see Return to the UK
Travel and borders
The Lebanese authorities have closed Lebanon’s borders, including Beirut Rafic Hariri Airport..
There are some exceptions to the closure. Those with Lebanese nationality, Lebanese residency or who are a member of a family of a Lebanese national should contact their nearest Lebanese Embassy.
If you are concerned about your visa expiring please contact General Security on 1717 or +961 (0) 1424668 for advice. General Security are currently extending visas and not issuing fines for visas that have expired since COVID19 restrictions have been introduced.
Public measures
The Lebanese authorities have extended the lock-down until at least the 24 May 2020. However, the Government has also announced a 5 stage process to ease some restrictions on movement and services, though implementation may vary and restrictions may be tightened again at short notice. Current restrictions include:
Individuals are advised to remain at home and restrict movement to essential movement only. Those over the age of 65 years old are advised to stay home and not go out unless absolutely necessary.
Public and private gatherings are banned.
There should be no movement from 2100 to 0500.
Face masks covering the mouth and nose must be worn when outside the home.
Individuals must maintain a safe distance from one another and avoid crowded areas.
Traffic is banned between 2100 and 0500. Vehicles with license plates ending in 1,3,5,7 or 9 are only permitted to move on Mondays, Wednesdays, Fridays and Sundays. Vehicles with license plates ending in 0,2,4,6 or 8 are only permitted to move on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Saturdays and Sundays. There are exemptions for military and security forces, the International Committee for the Red Cross, diplomatic and specific health and food industry related vehicles.
Private cars containing more than two people may be stopped.
All public transport is suspended.
There may be difficulties accessing taxis
Public departments, municipalities, unions, universities, public and private schools are closed, with the exception of core institutions, including security agencies, hospitals, pharmacies and banks (though ATMs and electronic transfers are functioning).
Lebanese authorities may issue fines, impose road blocks, or imprison those violating these restrictions for up to three years. You should comply with all local restrictions introduced by the Lebanese authorities and obey instructions of the security forces. These restrictions may be changed at short notice.
Keep up to date with information from your tour operator, transport or accommodation provider on the impact on any existing travel plans. If you need further information about entry requirements, contact the local immigration authorities or the nearest Lebanese embassy.
Further information
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
You can call the Lebanese Ministry of Health Coronavirus Hotline on +961 1 5494459. British nationals in Lebanon should comply with local restrictions and monitor local media for updates.
